# Golden / fixture / JSON contract files MUST be checked out with LF on every
# platform. Go tests compare expected bytes verbatim; Windows' default
# core.autocrlf=true silently injects \r before each \n on checkout, which
# breaks every `assertGolden`-style assertion with the tell-tale "want and got
# look identical but differ by exactly N bytes" diff (one \r per line).
#
# Scope: anything a Go test reads back via os.ReadFile and byte-compares.
*.golden            text eol=lf
*.json              text eol=lf
testdata/**         text eol=lf
**/testdata/**      text eol=lf

# Shell scripts must be LF (Windows runners execute them via bash from
# Git for Windows, which rejects CRLF shebangs).
*.sh                text eol=lf

# Go sources: enforce LF so gofmt / CI gofmt audit isn't fighting CRLF.
*.go                text eol=lf

# CRLF-emitting golden CSVs: writeReportRows / formatter csv.go set
# csv.Writer.UseCRLF=true (per csvcrlf_contract_test.go) so the on-disk
# fixture MUST keep \r\n. The broad `testdata/** text eol=lf` rule above
# was stripping the \r on every checkout, breaking byte-exact golden
# comparisons with a 1-byte-per-line drift. More-specific rules win, so
# pin these CSVs to CRLF (and `binary` to belt-and-suspenders disable
# any future text munging like BOM/whitespace fixers).
gitmap/clonefrom/testdata/clonefrom_report_*.csv  -text eol=crlf
gitmap/formatter/testdata/scan_*.csv              -text eol=crlf